        Old Dominion Freight Line stays on record profit, revenue pace in second quarter
    


By Richard Craver
Winston-Salem Journal







Richard Craver



















11 min ago
 (…)


























































































Old Dominion Freight Line Inc. kept on trucking toward its first $3 billion revenue year in the second quarter while reporting Thursday record net income.The Thomasville less-than-truckload company, a top-10 U.S. carrier, had $94.4 million in net income, up 20.9 percent.Diluted earnings rose 21 cents to $1.19.The average forecast was $1.09 by nine analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment Research. Analysts typically do not include one-time gains and charges in their forecasts.On the revenue side, Old Dominion had an 11.2 percent jump to $839.9 million.For the first half of fiscal 2017, revenue is at $1.59 billion, up 8.9 percent over last year. It just missed $3 billion in fiscal 2016.The overall results are likely to encourage investors to send Old Dominion roaring past its 52-week share price high of $100.71 in early trading today.Old Dominion’s record performance centers on gaining market share through adding and expanding centers. As a less-than-truckload carrier, it ships products more quickly and attracts more customers because it does not depend on a full trailer to make a profit.“These were the best growth rates in revenue and earnings per share since our first quarter of 2015,” David Congdon, the company’s vice chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.Congdon credited the revenue surge to increased demand and customers shipping heavier or larger orders.“We believe that the growth in (less-than-truckload) tonnage was attributable to the continued improvement in the domestic economy and the consistent execution of our long-term strategic plan of delivering superior service at a fair price,” Congdon said.For example, he said Old Dominion continues to maintain an on-time delivery rate of better than 99 percent.“With revenue growth continuing into the third quarter, we intend to hire additional employees so that we can continue to deliver superior service and position ourselves to win additional market share,” he said.However, Old Dominion’s strong annual performances of recent years have left it susceptible to investors’ and analysts’ higher earnings expectations.For example, Seeking Alpha contributor Stephen Simpson said before the earnings report that “Old Dominion shares have done well on the back of a good recovery in tonnage and prices.”“The growth of e-commerce and a greater focus on streamlined supply chains are creating new opportunities in less-than-truckload trucking that arguably play to Old Dominion's strengths in information technology and service.”Simpson cautioned Old Dominion “is back to what I would call its more typical valuation situation – relatively expensive compared to its likely medium/long-term earnings and cash flow prospects unless you are willing to give a relatively generous premium for its superior quality.”“One of the more persistent bear arguments on Old Dominion is that the company is about as well-run as it can be and it's going to be hard for the company to continue outperforming.
“In fact, some go as far as to argue that the service improvement efforts under way at Saia and other LTLs are whittling away Old Dominion's competitive advantages and that the company is due for a stretch of underperformance as a result.”Stifel analyst David Ross said Old Dominion's key to recent success "is that its network is better set up to benefit from additional volume due to the efficiency of its operation.""Incremental freight comes on at very low incremental cost, as opposed to other networks which might require more purchased transportation, dock labor, training costs, etc. to handle additional business.""It's knowing the cost of its network and using that knowledge as a tool to price freight and direct volume and density into the appropriate channels to maximize profitability," Ross said.Old Dominion had, at last count, 869 employees at its headquarters in Thomasville, 670 at a service center in Greensboro and 17,578 full-time employees overall, down 49 from a year ago.Old Dominion spent $16.5 million on cash dividends this fiscal year — the first in which it offered a dividend. It also spent $7.1 million on share repurchases, leaving $192.8 million on an authorized $250 million program.The company spent $131.3 million on capital investments during the quarter. It now projects spending $400 million during fiscal 2017: $185 million for real estate and service center expansions; $170 million for tractors and trailers (up $15 million); and $45 for information technology and other projects.Old Dominion said increased spending on tractors and trailers “is consistent with the company’s historical practice of reinvesting in its business to support long-term market share gains by ensuring it has the capacity to meet the service expectations of its customers.”






rcraver@wsjournal.com(336) 727-7376@rcraverWSJ














































